listitem.para:
it can be used as a simple, basic CMS. The user interface allows
        to edit pages visually, add and delete pages and do other basic tasks.
        This kind of approach should be easy enough for everyone;

multi-site support - multiple
        sites can be served with a single installation on a single
        context;

compatible with other editors -
        since it is file-based, you can edit your files with other programs if
        you want, then upload them as usual;

support for themes - uses
        SiteMesh as
        engine;

the theme main file: a JSP page named
          main.jsp that defines the common part of the
          pages and where the variable parts must be inserted;

open the File Manager and
          create a new HTML file in the desired place. Please keep in mind how
          the site map is created;

Create a new child page: available if
              that page can have children (see  for
              details);

Visually editable types: a
          comma-separated list of file types that can be edited using the
          wysiwyg editor;

Use high quality thumbnails by
          default: if selected, the file manager and the gallery
          module will create thumbnails with a better quality;

Server name: the name of the
          server used to send e-mail messages when a visitor compiles a mail
          form;

Destination directory: the
          local path of the exported copy, i.e. where the site will be
          exported (required);

CMS enabled: a flag that
          indicates that the CMS is active in that website (otherwise it is
          just a static website);

maxchars: maximum length of the
            excerpt for each article (default as per site
            configuration);

history: shows a link to previous
            articles, true (default) or
            false;

keywords: shows keywords (tags) after
            each article, true (default) or
            false;

readlink: shows a link to the full
            article after the excerpt, true (default) or
            false;

step: step for item css classes
            (default 1 - use 0 to remove
            classes);

form_css: the ccs class of the
            div that contains the entire form. The default
            value is mailform;

field_css: the css class of the
            individual form fields. The default value is
            formfields;

parse: if true (and
            if html is false),
            activates hyperlinks in comments (default
            false);

moderated: hides comments until
            approved by an authenticated user (default
            false);

date-style: CSS style used to tag the
            date used for sorting (default =
            diary-date);

captions: defines if the captions
            must be shown or not. Values are true (default)
            and false;

section.para:
form_css: the ccs class of the div that contains the entire form. The default value is mailform;
field_css: the css class of the individual form fields. The default value is formfields.
Note: There is a bug in Internet Explorer 6 that affects the display of the textarea form component. This results in the textarea being resized inappropriately as soon as text is entered into it. The workaround is to explicitly set the width of the div containing the form, and to set the width of the contained fields to 100%. The default ccs for the mailform and formfields styles does this to avoid the bug, be aware of this if you choose to modify or override these styles.

listitem.para:
the reset field inserts a reset button. A
            label can be specified as for the submit
            button;

the sender attribute indicates that the
            field value is to be used as the email address of the
            sender;

the required attribute may be specified to
            make a field mandatory. Required fields are shown in bold by
            default;

the messagebody attribute can be used to
            identify the field to be used as the body of the generated
            email;

allowHiding: defines if the module
            honours the "hide submenu" option or not. Values are
            false (default) and true;

dropScripts: if
            true, <script> tags are
            discarded (default false);

defaultValue: same as
            value, but will be set only if not found in
            the URL;

defaultName: a default file to be
            used if the searched file is not found. This default file is
            supposed to exist in the theme directory;

location (required): the name of the
            module location. All modules in a theme must have
            different location names;

alt: a string that is inserted when
            the module is not used (default
            &nbsp;);

Clean HTML: a link to edit
            the source of the current page after having it cleaned with jTidy,
            that tries to convert any page into well-formed XHTML;

root: the root path from which pages
            are included in the feed (defaults to the path of the current
            page);

path: the path used as root for the
            menu. Defaults to the path of the page to which the theme is
            applied;

path: the path used as root for the
            menu. Defaults to the path of the page to which the theme is
            applied;

allowHiding: defines if the module
            honours the "hide submenu" option or not. Values are
            false (default) and true;

allowHiding: defines if the module
            honours the "hide submenu" option or not. Values are
            false (default) and true;

mode: the type of breadcrumbs.
            Possible values are titles (default) and
            links;

current: boolean value to
            include/exclude the current page (default is
            true);

pre: a text to be added before the
            first element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
            all;

welcome: if true,
            the welcome page in the directory is included too (default
            true);

current: boolean value to
            include/exclude the current page (default is
            true);

pre: a text to be added before the
            first element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
            all;

pre: a text to be added before the
            first element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
            all;

post: a text to be added after the
            last element. It won't be added if there are no elements at
            all;

date: the format of the date.
            Possible values are normal (default) and
            full;

create a directory for each language, making sure that the
          each directory is named after a language code (i.e. en
          and it in our example);
